---
Every event dict produced by EventDetector (app/services/event_detector.py) must
contain exactly these six keys — no more, no fewer:

  city        (str)      — one of: "Ottawa", "Toronto", "Vancouver"
  event_type  (str)      — one of the ten strings listed below
  timestamp   (datetime) — timezone-aware UTC datetime from the RawReading
  summary     (str)      — one human-readable sentence; must include the city name,
                           the key numeric value, and the unit
  reason      (str)      — explains WHY it fired; must include the actual measured
                           value AND the threshold that was crossed
  metrics     (dict)     — all numeric values referenced in reason; threshold-based
                           events must include a "threshold" key

ALLOWED event_type VALUES (exactly these ten strings):
  sudden_temp_drop       — city-adaptive threshold (2× recent stddev, min 5.0°C)
  sudden_temp_rise       — same adaptive threshold
  city_anomaly           — z-score > 2.0 against city's own recent baseline
  feels_like_gap         — apparent vs actual temperature divergence > 8.0°C
  dangerous_wind         — wind speed > 80.0 km/h (Environment Canada criterion)
  wind_shift             — single-poll wind speed change > 40.0 km/h
  heavy_precipitation    — hourly precipitation > 10.0 mm
  precip_streak          — 3 consecutive readings each > 0.5 mm
  weather_code_severity  — WMO code escalates to a higher severity tier
  cross_city_divergence  — one city > 15.0°C from the average of the other two

METRIC KEYS — required keys per event type:
  sudden_temp_drop / sudden_temp_rise:
    previous_temperature, temperature, delta, threshold
  city_anomaly:
    temperature, mean, stddev, z_score
  feels_like_gap:
    temperature, apparent_temperature, gap
  dangerous_wind:
    wind_speed, threshold, excess_over_threshold
  wind_shift:
    previous_wind_speed, wind_speed, delta, threshold
  heavy_precipitation:
    precipitation, threshold, excess_over_threshold, multiplier
  precip_streak:
    streak_length, total_precipitation, readings
  weather_code_severity:
    previous_weather_code, weather_code, previous_tier, new_tier
  cross_city_divergence:
    temperature, other_average, divergence, other_cities

EXAMPLE of a correctly-formed event:
{
  "city": "Ottawa",
  "event_type": "feels_like_gap",
  "timestamp": "2024-01-15T14:00:00+00:00",
  "summary": "Ottawa feels 11.0°C colder than the thermometer reads: apparent -6.0°C vs actual 5.0°C (wind chill).",
  "reason": "Apparent temperature (-6.0°C) deviates 11.0°C from actual (5.0°C), exceeding the 8.0°C gap threshold. The gap is driven by wind chill.",
  "metrics": {"temperature": 5.0, "apparent_temperature": -6.0, "gap": 11.0}
}

NOTE on adaptive thresholds: sudden_temp_drop and sudden_temp_rise use a
city-adaptive threshold (max(5.0, stddev×2) from recent history). The resolved
threshold must always appear in metrics["threshold"].
